description: Borrowed from Latin innātus (“inborn”), perfect active participle of innāscor (“be born in, grow up in”), from in (“in, at on”) + nāscor (“be born”); see natal, native.

entries.meaning: Inborn; existing or having existed since birth.
(philosophy) Originating in, or derived from, the constitution of the intellect, as opposed to acquired from experience.

examples: As if she held the clue to something secret in his breast, of the nature of which he was hardly informed himself. As if she had an innate knowledge of one jarring and discordant string within him, and her very breath could sound it.

entries.meaning: (botany) Joined by the base to the very tip of a filament.

verbs.description: innate (third-person singular simple present innates, present participle innating, simple past and past participle innated)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To cause to exist; to call into being.
